      <byline class="print_byline">By Elisabeth Malkin (NYT)</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Malkin, Elisabeth</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Telefonos de Mexico is buying control of Brazil's largest long-distance carrier Embratel from WorldCom for $360 million; will acquire almost 20 percent economic interest in Embratel and almost 52 percent of voting shares (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Teléfonos de México said it was buying control of Brazil's largest long-distance carrier Embratel from WorldCom for $360 million. The Mexican telephone giant will acquire an almost 20 percent economic interest in Embratel and almost 52 percent of the voting shares. The sale is subject to approval by the American bankruptcy court handling WorldCom's restructuring. A consortium of Brazil's three largest fixed-line carriers plans to challenge the sale in court.</p>
        <p>Elisabeth Malkin (NYT)</p>
      </block>
